[Leviticus 9:22](../../../bib/kjv/lev009.htm#022.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_022">lev 9:22</span></span>

his hand: or, as the Greek has it, "his hands", Menachem gives reason
why it is written hand, to signify the right hand, because that was
lifted up higher than the left. The lifting up of the hand was a gesture
used in speaking, and signifying any weighty thing, [Isa
49:22](../../../bib/kjv/isa049.htm#022.md); and particularly in swearing,
[Gen 14:22](../../../bib/kjv/gen014.htm#022.md); praying, [Psa
28:2](../../../bib/kjv/psa028.htm#002.md); and blessing, either of God,
[Psa 134:2](../../../bib/kjv/psa134.htm#002.md), or of men, as in this
place. Paul, speaking of prayer, uses the phrase, "lifting up holy
hands;" as also David: "Let the lifting up of my hands be as the evening
sacrifice." [Gen 14:18-20](../../../bib/kjv/gen014.htm#018.md); [Num
